	\section{Development Description}
	\label{sec:dev}

	This section describes the steps of the development, also including their purposes and roles in the final work.
	
		% PCB schematic and Layout
		\subsection{PCB Creation}
		The first part of this experiment consisted in the creation of a Printed Circuit Board (PCB). It will be used as a interfacing module of the EPOSMoteII with RS232 (serial communication standard used in a large amount of peripherals and in the industry). This PCB would be responsible to do the communication between the charge controller of the boat and the EPOSMoteII.
		
		First, a schematic of the PCB was made (REFERENCIA FIGURA). The schematic consisted in two different parts; one part was responsible for the energy source of the PCB and the EPOSMoteII. The input voltage of 12 Volts has to be adjusted to 3.3 Volts (EPOSMoteIIs working-voltage). The second part of the schematic was the part responsible for the communication between the boats equipments and the EPOSMoteII (using RS232 standard).
		
		Once the schematic and the layout of the board were finished (REFERENCIA IMAGEM), the PCBs were actually manufactured (REFERENCIA IMAGEM).
		
		%Parsers Implementation
		\subsection{Parsers Integration}
		With the PCB done, next step we were to create two EPOSMoteII applications that integrate the parsers for the protocols of the boats equipment. These applications extract the relevant data to apply the telemetry. These data will then be sent to an base-station. 
		
		The first application implemented gathered the data of a battery monitor (BMV 600s of Victron Energy). The parser was made to work with any type of input data (negative, positive numbers and irrelevant inputs, witch is "---"). The messages sent by the battery monitor has the format show in (REFERENCIA FIGURA).
		
		Next step, the second application was implemented. This application used the Modbus communication standard to extract data from the charge controller (TriStar Solar Controller TS-60 of MorningStar Corporation). 
		
		Both applications created worked in the same way; first, all the data is received, then a buffer organizes them with the same format of the battery monitor messages. The data, once organized, is sent in one package in the WSN.
		
